record.Title: Waterfront in the vicinity of Main St., Seattle, Washington, ca. 1892.
record.Notes: Shows unidentified steamboat at the Union Pacific dock or City dock (foot of Main)<br>The canoe in foreground was copied and pasted from Boyd and Braas 22.<br><br>According to Paul Dorpat, Seattle Now and Then I, 1984: The Oregon Improvement Company filled the waterfront between its coal docks off King Street and Yesler's wharf with two large pier sheds it designated as simply A and B. The area between these sheds and the business district along First Avenue S. was, neither entirely filled nor covered. Thus up until the mid-90s, it was still possible for native dugouts to make their way between the Oregon piers and up under the overhead quay to their Ballast island.
